    <body>
      <head>Bertha Eissler (<hi rend="italic">née</hi> Riesz)</head>
      <div>

        <p>Member of the <ref cRef="entity-003218">Eissler family</ref>, of which notably <ref
            cRef="entity-000199">Jenny Eissler</ref> was a patron of Schenker's in the 1900s. </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <head>Bertha Eissler and Schenker</head>
        <p>The wife of Hugo Eissler, Bertha Eissler is mentioned twice in Schenker's diary. On
          October 1, 1907: "Mrs Bertha Eissler surpises me with a strange request" (OJ 1/6, p. 51).
          Then on January 31, 1908: "Mrs B. E. appears for the second time with strangely hysterical
          suggestions. A puzzle ‒ if otherwise underlying it there is not simple lasciviousness on
          the part of a woman given over to erotic impulses. But should she then really become more
          intimately acquainted with me?" (OJ 1/7, p. 69).</p>
      </div>
